## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread when it exceeds a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`, `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op, and `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown. All three must go.

### APIs to remove

| Removed API | Why |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No-op / obsolete |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if work() itself never checks the token.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If the caller can be async (preferred)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and should cooperate with cancellation

Pass the token through so the work can check it:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Then the caller cooperates:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls for this migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is not immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, which injected an exception anywhere, `CancellationToken` only works at checkpoints. If `work()` never checks the token, **it keeps running** — you just stop waiting for it. |
| **Fire-and-forget thread leak** | `Task.WaitAsync` returns when the token fires, but the underlying task may still be running. If `work()` holds resources (DB connections, file locks), you must pass the token in and check it. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch your own timeout — not an unrelated cancellation from an outer scope. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always `using`. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` cleanup logic** | Your original catch re-absorbed the abort to keep the thread alive. That pattern has no equivalent — instead, check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and decide whether to continue. |

### Uncooperative code (can't modify `work`)

If the work delegate calls code you don't control (e.g., a native/third-party blocking call), cooperative cancellation won't stop it. In that case, move the work to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only reliable way to forcibly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET.
